answers.body_markdown:
Because the ternary `? :` operator is still a single expression, which must still have a single type, because Java is statically typed. As a result, the types must match or be made to match. If the types cannot be made to match, an error results. However, a `char` can be implicitly converted to an `int` but not vice versa, so that is exactly what happens, as per the integer promotion rules.

The reason why `System.out.print(1 == 0 ? i : g);` causes the implicit conversion but not `System.out.print(1 == 0 ? 0 : g);` is because 0 is a **constant expression** already representable as a `char` but `i` is not, because `i` is a variable of type `int`.

From the [Specification](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se7/html/jls-15.html#jls-15.25):
&gt;The type of a conditional expression is determined as follows:
&gt;
&gt;...
&gt;
&gt;* If one of the operands is of type T where T is byte, short, or char, and the other operand is a constant expression (&#167;15.28) of type int whose value is representable in type T, then the type of the conditional expression is T.
&gt;
&gt; ...
&gt;
&gt;* Otherwise, binary numeric promotion ([&#167;5.6.2](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se7/html/jls-5.html#jls-5.6.2)) is applied to the operand types, and the type of the conditional expression is the promoted type of the second and third operands.

